Today (01-12-24)

  1. Downgraded Falcon 500’s to V5 2023
  2. Uninstalled tuner X software
  3. Reflashed Robo-Rio 2 with clean firmware
  4. Reinstalled Phoenix libraries for Labview
  5. Deployed a basic labview code running a motor for testing purposes and to put code on the rio
  6. At this point, we opened Phoenix Tuner and our CAN devices would not populate
  7. We verified that the CAN loop was correct and also isolated it all to one single Falcon motor
  8. Still, no CAN devices were found
  9. Removed Falcon motor
  10. Hooked up a PCM in place of the motor in the CAN and still not read by Phoenix Tuner
  11. Verified that a basic code using a limit switch talking to the front panel can be deployed and still functions as it should. This verifies we can still talk to the Rio and Labview still functions and the front panel is working.

If you’re unable to see the motors in the tuner at all, I’d take a step back. Anything code related isn’t going to be successful.

Keep in mind, that tool is meant to be how you interact with the motor controllers prior to coding. As it’s meant to be how you configure the motors, you’ll need to be successful with that before doing any code.

I like step 7. When you say “isolated it all to one single Falcon motor” do you mean you found one that was problematic? Or, you reduced your system down to a single motor? When reducing, can I assume you left a roboRIO and PDP/PDH in the loop? Mostly, I’m wanting to see that you have a healthy CAN bus.

Here is our troubleshooting log. We temporarily took all our motors and encoders off the can bus except for one. no change. We were able to see and install all using phoenix x. We were trying to avoid using x at all since it and its most recent 2024 firmware is not natively LabVIEW compatible. Afterward classic Phoenix tuner can communicate, but LabVIEW cannot. We can initialize run standard ancient PWM motor controllers and communicate with the rio using LabVIEW code in debug but cannot successfully run any CTRE motors. Please see the live doc below for more details.

(CTRE troubleshooting - Google Docs)

Check our log, if TLDR - It appears that installing Labview to the Rio using original tuner wont work for us, but once you have you have tried it from tuner and the file it writes is bad you have to wipe the Rio with a reimage it to install it clean from tuner x, otherwise tuner x wont pave over the existing Labview on the Rio when it sees it, it just throws an "already there message even though you want it to burn over it wont, so if you have already tried to use OG tuner I would try wiping the Rio. I thought since we were a Labview team we wanted to avoid using tuner x, but appeared in this step using tuner version of same file burn to Labview would not work on the Rio.

Don’t know if this will help but we had to do a mass compile (twice to get everything compiled ). This ensured that all the library routines and user code had fresh compiles. With thr project open, high light yhe project item , right click and select mass compile. Take a break then do it again. This assume that the library is loaded onto the rio using phoenix tuner x ( miscrosoft store ). Select advanced settings and install Labview libraries.
